\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Within-Firm Aggregation:
 Leontief to (Aggregate) Leontief
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin with the within-firm aggregation.
 All variables discussed in this section have an implicit firm subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

,
 which we drop for notational simplicity.
 But reader should have in mind that the analysis of the current subsection is for a single firm.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose tasks 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 are completed manually and tasks 
\begin_inset Formula $k+1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 are completed using AI.
 Given that the job design is fixed,
 we can treat hand-offs as standalone tasks with 
\begin_inset Formula $c=0$
\end_inset

 and time requirement 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{j}^{s}$
\end_inset

.
 We assume all hand-offs are executed manually by the worker who completes the last task of the job.
 This allows us to change the order in which tasks are completed without loss.
 Specifically,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}=\{1,\cdots,k\}$
\end_inset

 denote the set of AI-executed and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}=\{k+1,\cdots,n,n+1,n+J-1\}$
\end_inset

 denote the set of human-executed tasks.
 The task-level production function of the firm can be written in the following Leontief form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
1=\min\,\{\frac{l_{1}}{t_{1}^{m}\,\alpha^{-d_{1}}}\,,\,\cdots\,,\,\frac{l_{k}}{t_{k}^{m}\,\alpha^{-d_{k}}}\,,\,\frac{l_{k+1}}{t_{k+1}^{h}}\,,\,\cdots\,,\,\frac{l_{n}}{t_{n}^{h}}\,,\,\frac{l_{s^{1}}}{t_{1}^{s}}\,,\,\cdots\,,\,\frac{l_{s^{J-1}}}{t_{J-1}^{s}}\}.\label{eq:task_level_prod}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here,
 the left hand side is the firm's output (i.e.,
 the industry good) normalized to 1,
 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the amount of labor assigned to task 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 per unit of output,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{s^{j}}$
\end_inset

 is the amount of labor dedicated to do the hand-off between job 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j+1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:task_level_prod"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 implicitly assumes the firm's automation strategy and job design is fixed.
 That is,
 it takes the allocation of tasks to AI or human execution (hence,
 the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

) as well as the job boundaries as given.
 Thus,
 the required amount of time to spend on each task is fixed for the firm and it treats all parameters in the denominator of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:task_level_prod"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 as given.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the Leontief nature of production,
 equilibrium allocation of inputs to tasks is fixed at
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=\frac{l_{1}}{t_{1}^{m}\,\alpha^{-d_{1}}}=\cdots=\frac{l_{k}}{t_{k}^{m}\,\alpha^{-d_{k}}}=\frac{l_{k+1}}{t_{k+1}^{h}}=\cdots=\frac{l_{n}}{t_{n}^{h}}=\frac{l_{s^{1}}}{t_{1}^{s}}=\cdots=\frac{l_{s^{J-1}}}{t_{J-1}^{s}}.
\]

\end_inset

For each firm,
 the ratio of amount of labor assigned to any two input 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 above (regardless of mode of execution) is independent of units of output produced and wage rates,
 and depends only on the relative time requirements of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

,
 which are fixed.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{l_{i}}{l_{j}}=const_{ij}.\label{eq:fixed_labor_ratio}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The fixed ratio of labor inputs implies that the rate of substitution between any pair of tasks is independent of amount dedicated to production of other tasks.
 That is,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{∂}{∂l_{z}}\left(\frac{\frac{\Delta x}{\Delta l_{i}}}{\frac{\Delta x}{\Delta l_{j}}}\right)=0\qquad\qquad\forall z\neq i,j.\label{eq:task_subst_rate_indep}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A necessary and sufficient condition for aggregating a firm's production function from a Leontief with an input for each task to a Leontief with (firm-level) aggregate human labor and AI labor inputs is that the rate of substitution between any two tasks of the same aggregated type is independent of any task in the other aggregated type (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Leontief, 1947"
target "https://www.jstor.org/stable/1905335?seq=1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Fisher, 1965"
target "https://academic.oup.com/restud/article-abstract/32/4/263/1545778"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Felipe and Fisher, 2003"
target "https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/1467-999X.00166"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 In other words,
 the relative hired amount for any two human-executed tasks (respectively,
 AI-executed tasks) is only determined by tasks in the human-executed (respectively,
 AI-executed) group.
 The condition expressed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:task_subst_rate_indep"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 satisfies this property.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The condition in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:task_subst_rate_indep"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is in fact stricter than needed for obtaining the within-firm aggregation result.
 It not only satisfies our desired property but also provides a stronger requirement:
 that the rate of substitution between tasks within the same (firm-level) aggregate input type is also independent of other modules within that same aggregated input type.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus,
 we can represent the production function of the firm in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:task_level_prod"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
1=\min\,\{\frac{l_{M}}{\sum_{i=1}^{k}\,t_{i}^{m}\,\alpha^{-d_{i}}}\,,\,\frac{l_{H}}{\sum_{j=1}^{J-1}\,t_{j}^{s}+\sum_{i=k+1}^{n}\,t_{i}^{h}}\},\label{eq:task_level_agg_prod}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{H}$
\end_inset

 are the firm-aggregate AI labor and firm-aggregate human labor employed per unit of the industry good produced.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For ease of notation let us transform 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:task_level_agg_prod"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 into a more readable format by defining a few new variables.
 Define firm-level aggregate human and AI time requirements as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t_{M}=\sum_{i=1}^{k}\,t_{i}^{m},\label{eq:def_t_AI}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t_{H}=\sum_{j=1}^{J-1}\,t_{j}^{s}+\sum_{i=k+1}^{n}\,t_{i}^{h}\label{eq:def_t_H}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 be the composite,
 firm-level AI quality:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{\alpha}=\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{k}\,t_{i}^{m}\,\alpha^{-d_{i}}}{\sum_{i=1}^{k}\,t_{i}^{m}},\label{eq:alpha_bar}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t_{M}\,\bar{\alpha}=\sum_{i=1}^{k}\,t_{i}^{m}\,\alpha^{-d_{i}}.
\]

\end_inset

With these variables,
 we can rewrite 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:task_level_agg_prod"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
1=\min\,\{\frac{l_{M}}{t_{M}\ \bar{\alpha}}\,,\,\frac{l_{H}}{t_{H}}\}.\label{eq:micro_agg_prod}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This completes the within-firm aggregation step.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Across Firm Aggregation:
 (Aggregate) Leontief to CES
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next,
 we show that with the proper firm-level heterogeneity we can aggregate the firms' (aggregate) Leontief production functions into a CES industry production function with two inputs:
 industry-level aggregate human labor and industry-level aggregate AI labor.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume the industry-level production function is represented by the following CES form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=\left(\theta_{H}\ H^{\rho}\ +\ \theta_{M}\ M^{\rho}\right)^{\frac{1}{\rho}},\qquad\qquad\sigma=\frac{1}{1-\rho}.
\]

\end_inset

Here,
 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 represents the aggregate human labor and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 represents the aggregate AI labor at the industry level while 1 on the left-hand-side is the aggregate industry output.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Since the measure of firms is 1,
 production at the industry level also aggregates up to 1.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}=\frac{H}{M}$
\end_inset

 be the total human labor in units of total AI labor and rewrite the above as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
1=\left(\theta_{H}\ \tilde{H}^{\rho}\ +\ \theta_{M}\right)^{\frac{1}{\rho}}.\label{eq:macro_agg_prod}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The firm-level aggregate Leontief function specified in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:micro_agg_prod"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 implies that in equilibrium
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=\frac{l_{M}}{t_{M}\ \bar{\alpha}}=\frac{l_{H}}{t_{H}},
\]

\end_inset

and thus per unit of output human labor and AI labor for the firm is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
l_{M}=t_{M}\ \bar{\alpha},\qquad\qquad l_{H}=t_{H}.\label{eq:firm_labor}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Due to the fixed-proportions nature of production at the micro level,
 once the level of one input is specified the level of other input is pinned down by the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{H}/t_{M}\,\bar{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 each firm only has one degree of freedom in choosing its inputs.
 Because of this property we take just one of the inputs—
human labor 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{H}$
\end_inset

—
as the variable factor and treat the other—
AI labor 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{M}$
\end_inset

—
as a fixed proportion of the variable input:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
l_{M}=\frac{t_{M}\,\bar{\alpha}}{t_{H}}\,l_{H}\label{eq:fixed_proportions}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Firm-level Profitability Condition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{H}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{M}$
\end_inset

 be the output price-deflated wage rates for (homogenous) human and AI labor,
 respectively.
 A firm produces only if it gains nonnegative profits:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{H}\,l_{H}+w_{M}\,l_{M}\leq1.
\]

\end_inset

Given the fixed ratio property in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:fixed_proportions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 the profitability condition above can be written as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w_{H}\,l_{H}+w_{M}\left(\frac{t_{M}\ \bar{\alpha}}{t_{H}}l_{H}\right)=\left(w_{H}+w_{M}\frac{t_{M}\ \bar{\alpha}}{t_{H}}\right)l_{H}=w\,l_{H}\leq1.\label{eq:profitability_H}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Here 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is the time requirement-weighted human wage rate for when we only consider human labor as the input:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w=\frac{w_{H}t_{H}\ +\ w_{AI}t_{AI}\ \bar{\alpha}}{t_{H}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

 denote the distribution of relative (firm-)aggregate human and (firm-)aggregate AI time requirements.
 That is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t\sim g(t),\quad\text{where }\ t=\frac{t_{H}}{t_{M}\ \bar{\alpha}}\label{eq:g_definition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This definition implies that total industry-level output is 
\begin_inset Formula $1=\int_{0}^{\frac{1}{w}}\ g(t)\ dt$
\end_inset

 while the industry-aggregate variable input is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}=\int_{0}^{\frac{1}{w}}\ t\ g(t)\ dt$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To connect the industry-level aggregate CES production function and the micro level Leontief production functions we must link 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{H},\theta_{AI},\rho$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:macro_agg_prod"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 to some aggregate notion of individual firms variables in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:micro_agg_prod"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 This will be done by specifying the type of heterogeneity across firms,
 i.e.,
 the shape of the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
Assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho<0$
\end_inset

 (and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma<1$
\end_inset

)
\bar default
 so that the industry-level aggregate production exhibits some degree of complementarity we obtain the following analytical formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $g(.)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It would be nice to see how 
\begin_inset Formula $g(.)$
\end_inset

 changes as we vary 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 Unfortunately,
 depending on the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dg}{d\rho}$
\end_inset

 can be positive or negative.
 So,
 overall,
 the sign of derivative is inconclusive.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(t;\,\rho,\,\theta_{H},\,\theta_{M})=\frac{\theta_{H}^{\ \ -\frac{1}{\rho(\alpha(1-\rho))}}}{(1-\rho)\ \theta_{M}^{\ \ 1/\rho}}\ t^{-\frac{(2-\rho)}{\rho(1-\rho)}}\ \left[t^{\rho/(\rho-1)}\ \left(\frac{\theta_{M}}{\theta_{H}^{\ \ 1/(1-\rho)}}-1\right)\right]^{-(1+\rho)/\rho}.\label{eq:het_dist}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

See the Appendix for derivation details.
 Moreover,
 from standard CES results we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{H}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{M}$
\end_inset

 are the expenditure shares of corresponding inputs:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta_{H}=1-\theta_{M}=\frac{w_{H}\,\tilde{H}}{w_{M}+w_{H}\,\tilde{H}}=\frac{w_{H}\,\int_{0}^{\frac{1}{w}}\ t\ g(t)\ dt}{w_{M}+w_{H}\,\int_{0}^{\frac{1}{w}}\ t\ g(t)\ dt}.\label{eq:thetas}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This completed the across-firm aggregation step.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
From Relative Task Durations Heterogeneity to AI Quality Heterogeneity:
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:x_to_alpha"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now,
 we discuss how the heterogeneity in the ratio of human to AI time requirements can be mapped into differences in the AI quality level.
 Recall from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:g_definition"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 that density function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

 describes the distribution of the variable
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t=\frac{t_{H}}{t_{M}\ \bar{\alpha}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us fix the human and management time costs for all tasks,
 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{H}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{AI}$
\end_inset

 are fixed for a given job design and automation plan.
 With 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{H}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{M}$
\end_inset

 being fixed the variation in 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{t_{H}}{t_{M}\,\bar{\alpha}}$
\end_inset

 can be attributed solely to variation in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\alpha}$
\end_inset

,
 which captures firms’ varying capabilities to deploy AI effectively on similar tasks according to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:alpha_bar"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Denote the density of firm-level aggregate AI quality 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $h(\bar{\alpha})$
\end_inset

.
 Through a change-of-variable approach we obtain the following for 
\begin_inset Formula $h(\bar{\alpha})$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h(\bar{\alpha};\,\rho,\,\theta_{H},\,\theta_{M})=g(\frac{t_{H}}{t_{M}\ \bar{\alpha}};\,\rho,\,\theta_{H},\,\theta_{M})\ \bigg|\frac{dt}{d\bar{\alpha}}\bigg|=\frac{t_{H}}{t_{M}\ \bar{\alpha}^{2}}\ g(\frac{t_{H}}{t_{M}\ \bar{\alpha}};\,\rho,\,\theta_{H},\,\theta_{M}).\label{eq:AI_quality_dist}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:AI_quality_dist"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 characterizes the distribution of (firm-level aggregate) AI quality that is required for supporting an aggregate CES production function.
 Further fixing AI execution difficulty of AI chains 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}$
\end_inset

 will give a one to one mapping between 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 per equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:alpha_bar"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 This completes the aggregation from micro Leontief production functions with different AI quality levels to a macro CES production function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equilibrium Allocations when Human and AI Labor are of the Same Kind
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{H}=\frac{H}{M}=\int_{\theta_{H}^{-\frac{1}{\rho}}}^{\frac{1}{w}}\ t\ g(t)\ dt.\label{eq:macro_inputs_ratio}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The equilibrium amount of industry-level 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 will be determined based on supply of different kinds of inputs along with equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:macro_inputs_ratio"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume other than required trainings (captured through 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

 s) a worker can spend their time executing a manual task or managing an AI chain.
 In other words,
 assume human labor and AI labor are of the same kind.
 Suppose the homogenous labor has a total fixed supply of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 split between 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and the shared wage rate is 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 (i.e.,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{H}=w_{M}=w=v_{L}+\sum c_{i}$
\end_inset

).
 Labor market clearing implies:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L=H+M.\label{eq:total_labor_supply}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Substituting for 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:macro_inputs_ratio"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:total_labor_supply"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 gives total labor allocated to AI across the industry
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M=\frac{L}{1+\int_{\theta_{H}^{-\frac{1}{\rho}}}^{\frac{1}{w}}\ t\ g(t)\ dt}.\label{eq:AI_labor}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Similarly,
 the share of human labor in the industry will be
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H=\frac{L\ \int_{\theta_{H}^{-\frac{1}{\rho}}}^{\frac{1}{w}}\ t\ g(t)\ dt}{1+\int_{\theta_{H}^{-\frac{1}{\rho}}}^{\frac{1}{w}}\ t\ g(t)\ dt}.\label{eq:human_labor}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expression for industry-level AI employment has a nice comparative static result:
 AI employment goes up following an increase in AI quality 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 This is because,
 for a fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{H}/t_{M}$
\end_inset

,
 an increase in AI quality translates into 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

 shifting to the left in the first-order stochastic dominance sense.
 This shift reduces the denominator in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:AI_labor"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and thus industry-level AI deployment 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 increases.
\end_layout

